<article class="blog-post">
  <div class="post-header">
    <span class="post-title">&#128176; Fixed Cost</span>
    <span class="post-date">May 24th 2026</span>
  </div>
  <div class="post-body">
    <p>
      A fixed cost is a cost that stays the same even when your usage or
      activity changes. It does not care if you had a busy month, a slow month,
      or did almost nothing. The bill still shows up.
    </p>
    <p>
      That is why fixed costs matter: they create a baseline you must cover
      before anything feels profitable, flexible, or free.
    </p>
    <hr class="post-divider" />
    <p>
      <strong>&#128663; Example:</strong> car insurance. Even if you do not drive
      the car this month, you may still have to pay the insurance premium. In
      personal budgeting, that makes it a fixed expense. In a business, it can
      also be overhead because it supports operations indirectly.
    </p>
  </div>
